    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-09-13T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-09-13T03:00:00-05:00" n="51"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d51">
                <head>51. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Japan</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d51fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 611.94/9–1355. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <placeName>Tokyo</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                                when="1955-09-13T17:00:00+09:00">September 13, 1955—5 p.m.</date>
                        </hi>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>695. <persName corresp="#p_MTF1">Frank Matsumoto</persName>, who returned with
                        <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> September 10, called on
                        <persName>Parsons</persName> yesterday afternoon. Following highlights:</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> immensely pleased with trip and
                        so told Hatoyama when he and <persName corresp="#p_MTF1"
                            >Matsumoto</persName> reported in Karuizawa 11th. <persName
                            corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_KI1"
                            >Kono</persName> both now have good understanding American viewpoint and
                        this, in <persName corresp="#p_MTF1">Matsumoto</persName>’s opinion, most
                        important result of trip. <persName corresp="#p_KI1">Kono</persName>“changed
                        man” (for better) as result his contact with leaders in Europe and America.
                            <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> much impressed with
                        friendliness and essential similarity of viewpoint towards Japan of most
                        Americans he met including Senator <persName corresp="#p_GWF1"
                            >George</persName>, Governor Dewey<note n="2" xml:id="d51fn2">Thomas E.
                            Dewey, Governor of New York, 1943–1955; subsequently partner in the law
                            firm Dewey, Ballantine, Bushby, Palmer, and Wood.</note> and Paul
                        Hoffman who discussed Japanese-American economic questions with him at some
                        length. <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> believes Japan
                        cornerstone of U.S. policy in Far East.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KI1"
                            >Kono</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MTF1">Matsumoto</persName>
                        all continue fully agreed with Secretary’s view that mutual security treaty
                        proposed by <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Shigemitsu</persName> premature.
                            <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> considers <persName
                            corresp="#p_SM1">Shigemitsu</persName> grossly overplayed magnitude
                        Communist threat within Japan in mistaken argument for treaty. Discussion
                        mutual security treaty nevertheless of value because behind scenes in Tokyo
                        idea going around that if Japan wants equality and status as major power, it
                        must accept obligations as well as benefits of collective security whether
                        with U.S. or in U.N.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> and Bukichi Miki had been agreed
                        on easing <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Shigemitsu</persName> out of office.
                            <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> could have him removed at
                        any time. However, notwithstanding <persName corresp="#p_KN1"
                            >Kishi</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KI1">Kono</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_MTF1">Matsumoto</persName> dissatisfaction with <persName
                            corresp="#p_SM1">Shigemitsu</persName>’s handling of Washington talks,
                            <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> had decided <persName
                            corresp="#p_SM1">Shigemitsu</persName> should not be eased out now for
                        fear would undercut value Japanese-American talks.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> had made good impression in U.S.
                            <persName corresp="#p_MTF1">Matsumoto</persName> had privately praised
                        his performance and loyal cooperation to Hatoyama. Therefore, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName>–Hatoyama relationship now on better
                        basis, also <persName corresp="#p_MTF1">Matsumoto</persName>’s own
                        position.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Former progressives (<persName corresp="#p_SM1">Shigemitsu</persName>’s
                        party) still opposing consolidation or merger conservatives. <persName
                            corresp="#p_KN1">Kishi</persName> now believes Hatoyama should be first
                        president of consolidated party.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AJM1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Allison</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
